	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Regional integration is the key to export diversification</h1>

			
			<h4>
												10 June 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A World Bank study published in March has identified the process of regional integration in sub-Saharan Africa as critical to future export diversification. Although sub-Saharan Africa’s exports have been buoyant, this has been largely due to rising world prices for major primary product exports, most of which are minerals rather than agricultural commodities.</p><p>This is reflected in the geographical pattern of export growth: the World Bank found that ‘the fastest rates of merchandise export growth were experienced by Southern African countries, especially SACU ones (most notably South Africa) as well as non-COMESA SADC countries. Goods exports from EAC countries’ – particularly precious metals – ‘grew more strongly towards the end of the period to keep pace with world export growth and those from ECOWAS largely stagnated.’</p><p>It is also reflected in the roller-coaster ride associated with reliance on minerals, the demand for which is heavily affected by growth in the world in general and, nowadays, in East and South Asia in particular. This is further reflected in the low level of linkages to the rest of the economy from the booming mineral sector, with unemployment rates remaining stubbornly high even in countries that have benefited most from the boom: unemployment in South Africa, for example, remains around 24%, while in Tanzania extreme income-poverty appears to have remained broadly constant at around 35% of the population.</p><p>The answer, according to the World Bank, is for sub-Saharan Africa ‘to diversify the export base away from dependence on primary commodities and find policies and processes that will improve the conditions of firms and individuals in the informal sector, increasing opportunities to interact with formal sector firms and providing a coherent route towards formality.’ By ‘primary commodities’, the authors are referring primarily to minerals since they note ‘the enormous opportunities for cross-border trade in agricultural products from food surplus to food deficit areas’. Regional integration can play a critical role in this process, lowering trade and operating costs and relaxing constraints in accessing the essential services and skills needed to boost productivity and diversify into higher value-added production.</p><p>EAC has so far made most progress in this direction. Progress has been less substantial so far in West Africa, but the EU is supporting the process as part of the EPA negotiation preparations. Nonetheless, much remains to be done. In some regions there remain significant tariff barriers to intra-regional trade, and in all of them there exist significant barriers to goods trade which is ‘typically hampered by a large number of NTBs’. These will not be dealt with by the Grand FTA being agreed for Eastern and Southern Africa even though this is expected to boost intra-regional trade to some extent.</p><p>The importance of removing technical barriers to regional agricultural trade is evident from the draft COMESA agreement to free seed trade across borders. This shows how an overarching FTA can be made more effective by supporting product- and issue-specific agreements. The draft deal on common standards for development, production, release and cross-border distribution of seeds for 12 crops could be endorsed by the COMESA Council of Ministers as soon as July 2011. It is expected to benefit regional seed companies.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
