				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Petroleum-exporting countries are sometimes said to suffer from a ‘resource curse’. The same associated problems apply to other commodities, such as copper, and are not limited to developing countries – the term ‘Dutch disease’ was coined by economists to describe the syndrome. Large volumes of foreign exchange are generated by industries, often operating within an enclave, that contribute few jobs to the economy but push up the exchange rate, making other exports less competitive and imports more competitive and generally pushing resources out of the productive sector into activities less vulnerable to import competition. When the mine or resource runs out – or there is a temporary slump in demand – the exporter may find that it is worse off than before the boom.</p><p>The word ‘commodity’ can be a misleading one since it applies both to minerals and to agricultural products. The ‘resource curse’ problems associated with mineral commodities to do not apply to agricultural ones. Production does not occur within an enclave (especially when farms are medium-sized or smaller). There are stronger linkages to the rest of the economy and more employment. At the same time, there can still be price booms and slumps (as is very evident now at a time of historically high world prices) which impact on the exchange rate, so careful economic management is required to avoid the effects of ‘Dutch disease’.</p><p>What needs to be done to overcome the problems of both mineral and agricultural commodities is well understood – but politically and technically hard to achieve. A key element is to support other areas of production, including more agriculture, and this is where enhanced intra-regional trade can make a contribution. No ACP country has a ‘large economy’ in terms of purchasing power, so all are disadvantaged to a greater or lesser degree in producing goods in which there exist economies of scale. A larger regional market can help some producers reach the minimum efficient scale of production. But there are dangers, as if the tariffs on extra-regional imports are too high, then all members may become poorer as they consume expensive regional goods in place of cheaper goods from, say, Asia. Tackling the physical and NTB barriers to intra-regional trade is one means of obtaining the benefits while avoiding the risks.</p>
		</div>
		
